data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code uses the **timeout enforcement** pattern — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit. It also catches `ThreadAbortException` and calls `Thread.ResetAbort`. All three APIs (`Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, `Thread.ResetAbort`) throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` or are obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) in .NET 6+.

### What changes and why

| .NET Framework API | Problem in .NET 8 | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource is IDisposable — always wrap in using.
        // CancelAfter schedules automatic cancellation after the timeout.
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run moves the work to the thread pool.
            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if the token
            // fires before the task completes — this is the .NET 6+
            // replacement for "abort after timeout".
            return Task.Run(() => work(), cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter()
                       .GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls for this migration

1. **Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** `Task.Run(() => work())` — if `work()` is a long-running CPU-bound call that never checks a token, it will continue running in the background even after the timeout fires. `WaitAsync` unblocks the *caller*, but the work itself keeps executing. If you need the work to actually stop, pass the token into `work`:

   ```csharp
   // Better: let the work cooperate
   public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
   {
       using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
       try
       {
           return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                      .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                      .GetAwaiter()
                      .GetResult();
       }
       catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
       {
           throw new TimeoutException(
               $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
       }
   }
   ```

   Then the caller inserts `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints inside the work delegate.

2. **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`.** It uses timers internally — leaking it leaks the timer. Always use `using`.

3. **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly.** The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures you only convert *your* timeout into `TimeoutException`, not someone else's cancellation.

4. **Truly uncooperative code** (third-party library, native call) that can't accept a token: move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. There is no in-process equivalent to `Thread.Abort` in modern .NET.
